'''Kyaku-shiki''' (格式, '''{{ill|Kyaku and Shiki|lt=laws and regulations|ja|格式|qq=draft}}''') refers to supplementary legal codes or legal compilations issued to complement the {{ill|Ritsuryō|ja|律令|qq=draft}} system. '''Kyaku''' (格) were laws (auxiliary statutes) and imperial edicts meant to revise or supplement the Ritsuryō, while '''Shiki''' (式/のり) were detailed regulations for implementing the Ritsuryō<ref>In Tang China, the Ritsuryō codes were defined as follows: Ritsu (律) "regulates crimes and punishments," Ryō (令) "sets norms and rules," Kyaku (格) "prohibits wrongdoings," and Shiki (式) "establishes procedures." Japan’s {{ill|Kōnin Kyaku-Shiki|ja|弘仁格式|qq=draft}} preface explains, "Ritsu is based on discipline, Ryō on admonishment, Kyaku establishes laws as per the times, and Shiki supplements omissions." However, definitions were inconsistent, with some laws being referred to as Kyaku or Shiki depending on context.</ref><ref>''{{ill|Hachiman Usa Shrine Oracles Collection|ja|八幡宇佐宮御託宣集|qq=draft}}''</ref>.

== Overview ==
The Ritsuryō system operated on '''Ritsu''' (律, criminal law), '''Ryō''' (令, administrative and civil law), '''Kyaku''' (格), and '''Shiki''' (式). The core laws (Ritsu and Ryō) were rarely amended; instead, Kyaku laws were issued to revise or add provisions, and Shiki laws provided detailed implementation guidelines. Individual laws were sometimes called "Kyaku of [a specific date]," and decrees or government orders were also broadly referred to as Kyaku<ref name="haya">Hayakawa (1995), pp. 286-289</ref>. 

Shiki often supplemented Ryō with phrases like "follow the Shiki" appearing in the {{ill|Yōrō Code|ja|養老律令|qq=draft}}. However, in practice, distinctions between Kyaku and Shiki were not always clear, as some Kyaku laws were codified and regulated under Shiki<ref name="haya"/>. Additionally, discrepancies existed between the original texts of imperial edicts or official orders and their versions recorded in Kyaku-Shiki due to updates or revisions during compilation to reflect the effective laws at the time<ref name="kawa">Kawashiri (2002), pp. 111-112</ref>.

The earliest known Kyaku-Shiki codes were the {{ill|Linzhi Kyaku|ja|麟趾格|qq=draft}} of 541 and the {{ill|Zhongxing Yongshi|ja|中興永式|qq=draft}} of 544, both in China<ref name="kawa"/>.

=== Differences in East Asia ===
While Kyaku and Shiki were essential supplements to the Ritsuryō system, their application varied across China, Japan, and Korea. 

In China, Kyaku and Shiki were often compiled and enacted alongside Ritsu and Ryō. However, in Japan, new laws issued via imperial decrees or government orders were later compiled into Kyaku-Shiki. Moreover, after the {{ill|Tang Dynasty|ja|唐|qq=draft}}'s fall, China's Kyaku laws became more limited in scope, whereas in Japan, Kyaku laws played an increasingly significant role, sometimes even overriding the Ritsuryō system (e.g., the {{ill|Konden Einen Shizai Law|ja|墾田永年私財法|qq=draft}}).

In Korea, particularly under {{ill|Silla|ja|新羅|qq=draft}}, the Ritsuryō codes were adopted from China, but Kyaku-Shiki laws were tailored to local circumstances.

=== Kyaku, Shiki, and Rei ===
Kyaku laws were typically arranged by department or office, with individual provisions including issue dates. Shiki not only provided implementation details for Ryō but also established rules for new offices, such as the {{ill|Office of Police and Justice|ja|検非違使|qq=draft}} (e.g., "Kenpeishi Shiki"). Similar to Shiki, there were also supplementary codes referred to as Rei.
*
